{{Infobox writer <!--For more information, see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]].--> | name = Benjamin Feigenbaum | honorific_prefix = | honorific_suffix = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = File:Benjamin_Feigenbaum_cartoon.png | image_size = | alt = | caption = "B. Feigenbaum, the most observant Marxist". Below caption says "Dedicated to extremist, blasphemous B. Feigenbaum, who rejects all gods except his own, Karl Marx.", (1912). | pseudonym = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date|1860|08|12}} | birth_place = [[Warsaw]], [[Poland]] | death_date = {{death date|1932|11|10}} | death_place = [[New York City]] | resting_place = [[Mount Carmel Cemetery (Queens, New York)|Mount Carmel Cemetery]], [[New York (state)|New York]] | occupation = Newspaper editor, satirist, translator | language = [[Yiddish]], [[English Language|English]], [[Polish Language|Polish]] | nationality = | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | period = | genre = <!-- or: | genres = --> | movement = | notableworks = <!-- or: | notablework = --> | spouse = Mathilda Feigenbaum<!-- or: | spouses = --> | partner = <!-- or: | partners = --> | children = 4 (including [[William M. Feigenbaum|William]], Henry, Belle Kanin and R. Ganetkin) | relatives = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | years_active = | module = | website = | portaldisp = <!-- "on", "yes", "true", etc; or omit --> | ethnicity = | subjects = Socialism, secularism <!-- or: | subjects = --> }}
'''Benjamin Feigenbaum''' (August 12, 1860 &ndash; November 10, 1932) was a [[Poles|Polish]] born [[Yiddish]] [[socialist]], newspaper editor, translator, and satirist. Feigenbaum was an associate editor of the Yiddish language papers ''[[The Forward]]'', its predecessor ''[[Di Arbeter Tsaytung]],'' and the literary monthly ''[[Di Tsukunft]]'' and a pioneer of the [[Socialist Party of America]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23373183/benjamin_feigenbaum_dies_leaving_4/|title=Feigenbaum Dies, Pioneer Socialist; Had been long ill|last=|first=|date=10 November 1932|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=2018-09-02|page=12|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/K2587506320/GPS?sid=wikipedia|title=Gale - User Identification Form|last=|first=|date=|website=link.galegroup.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-09-02}}</ref>
During Jewish Holiday of [[Yom Kippur]] in 1899, Feigenbaum famously said in alternative event ''"If there is a God and if he is Almighty as the clergy claims he is, I give him just two minutes’ time to kill me on the spot, so that he may prove his existence!"'' after two minutes he declared ''"See! There is no God!".'' Afterwards he announced a location for the workers to eat instead of fasting, as traditionally done during Yom Kippur.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.versobooks.com/blogs/2981-london-s-revolutionary-yiddishland|title=London’s Revolutionary Yiddishland|work=Versobooks.com|access-date=2018-07-27}}</ref>
== Early life == Benjamin Feigenbaum was born to a prominent [[Hasidic Judaism|Chassidic]] family in [[Warsaw]], [[Poland]]. He went to [[Yeshiva]]h, but became a free-thinker. According to a colleague, [[Israel Joshua Singer]], Feigenbaum's "conversion" to secularism happened when his teacher, the [[Ger (Hasidic dynasty)|Gerer]] rebbe, discovered that Feigenbaum was not wearing [[Tzitzit|tsitsit]], a ritual garb. The rebbe beat him as a punishment.<ref name="HoweLibo2005">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KlxAWCZmy2QC|title=World of Our Fathers|author1=Irving Howe|author2=Kenneth Libo|date=October 2005|publisher=NYU Press|isbn=978-0-8147-3685-2}}</ref><ref name=":2" />
Later on, he moved to Belgium; there he attended his first socialist protest in [[Antwerp]] in 1884.<ref name="Weinstein2018">{{cite book|author=Bernard Weinstein|title=The Jewish Unions in America: Pages of History and Memories|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0ndKDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT46|date=6 February 2018|publisher=Open Book Publishers|isbn=978-1-78374-356-8|pages=46–}}</ref> On December 25, 1886, his wife Matilda (Kaminsky) Feigenbaum gave birth to their son [[William M. Feigenbaum|William Morris Feigenbaum]]. He a total of 2 daughters and 2 sons named Kanin, R. Ganetkin, William and Henry.<ref name=":1" />
== Career ==
As a young socialist in 1887, Feigenbaum considered starting a socialist Yiddish newspaper. To his delight, he discovered the London-based ''[[Arbeter Fraynd]]'' recently started. He wrote them immediately. Towards the end of 1888, Feigenbaum moved to [[London]], [[United Kingdom|UK]] with his wife, to join their editorial board.<ref name="Weinstein2018" /><ref name="Mendelsohn1997">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Bw8WCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA72|title=Essential Papers on Jews and the Left|author=Ezra Mendelsohn|date=June 1997|publisher=NYU Press|isbn=978-0-8147-5571-6|pages=72–}}</ref>
In 1891, Feigenbaum immigrated to [[New York City|New York]], to work on New York's first Yiddish-language socialist newspaper, ''Di Arbeter Tsaytung'' (The Workman's Paper). He co-founded the [[Workmen's Circle]], serving as its first General-Secretary.<ref name=":0" /> In New York, Feigenbaum developed a relationship with [[Bolesław Miklaszewski]], a representative of the London affiliate of the [[Polish Socialist Party]] (PPS) called the Union of Polish Socialists Abroad (ZZSP). After vetting Feigenbaum's circles to ensure they did not have "a gravitational pull" to Russia, ZZSP announced creation of "Jewish Socialist Post from America to Poland" in 1896, to publish and disseminate Yiddish socialist literature.<ref name="Zimmerman2004">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6sbr9cZyw_4C&pg=PA127|title=Poles, Jews, and the Politics of Nationality: The Bund and the Polish Socialist Party in Late Tsarist Russia, 1892–1914|author=Joshua D. Zimmerman|date=26 January 2004|publisher=Univ of Wisconsin Press|isbn=978-0-299-19463-5|pages=127–}}</ref>
== Police retaliation == Feigenbaum was arrested during a brawl with the police on October 29, 1892 , shortly after giving a speech in [[Philadelphia]]. He was charged with inciting to riot, assaulting an officer and breaching the peace after allegedly hitting an officer with his cane. He was held on $600 bail.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23307268/pittsburgh_dispatch/|title=Clipping from Pittsburgh Dispatch - Newspapers.com|last=|first=|date=October 30, 1892|work=Pittsburgh Dispatch|access-date=2018-08-31|language=en}}</ref> In [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]] he was charged with inciting to riot, which were later dismissed by a Judge during trial in a higher court.<ref name="Weinstein20182">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0ndKDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT53|title=The Jewish Unions in America: Pages of History and Memories|author=Weinstein|first=Bernard|date=6 February 2018|publisher=Open Book Publishers|year=|isbn=978-1-78374-356-8|location=|pages=53–54}}</ref> In January, 1905, Providence police received a tip that an "anarchist provocateur" was scheduled to speak. Police surrounded the designated venue, disabling gas and cited lack of permit for as reason for shutting it down. The sponsors of the lecture, the Providence branch of [[Workmen's Circle]] obtained permits and scheduled another venue for Feigenbaum to speak at. If Hyman Goldsmith, a Yiddish speaking undercover police patrolman heard Feigenbaum mention anything about “[[Emma Goldman]]<nowiki/>ism” or “bomb throwing” the hall would be cleared immediately by other undercover police in crowd. Instead, Feigenbaum orated for two hours and 15 minutes about the compatibility of religion and socialism, in contrast with his earlier recitals. The police were ridiculed the following day by ''[[Daily Journal (Providence)|The Daily Journal]]'', ''[[The Evening Bulletin]]'', and ''[[The Providence Telegram]].''<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.jvhri.org/stories/When-the-Socialist-came-to-town,1525?|title=When ‘the Socialist’ came to town|last=Foster|first=Geraldine S.|date=November 13, 2015|work=The Jewish Voice|access-date=2018-09-01|publisher=Jewish Alliance of Greater Rhode Island|language=en}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite journal|last=Ingall|first=Carol K.|date=November 1979|title=The Day The Anarchists Came to Town|url=http://www.rijha.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/8-1-Nov-79.pdf|journal=Rhode Island Jewish Historical Notes|volume=8|issue=1|pages=95-97|via=}}</ref>
== Criticism of zionism and religion == ''<nowiki/><nowiki/><nowiki/><nowiki/><nowiki/><nowiki/><nowiki/><nowiki/><nowiki/>'' Feigenbaum was highly critical of [[Zionism]] and the usage of biblical scriptures to promoting ''socialist spiritualization''. In his Yiddish article, ''<nowiki/>'Materialism in Judaism or Religion and Life'<nowiki/>'' (1896), Feigenbaum criticized using the [[Bible]] as 'propaganda'. If [[Jeremiah]] did not know [[Karl Marx|Marx]], then it was disingenuous to claim that Marxism is part of a prophetic tradition. In ''<nowiki/>'Vi Kumt a yid tsu sotsyialismus''' (How does a Jew come to socialism?) Feigenbaum writes ''"Yes, brothers, socialism is redemption for us, the Jews. Socialism will rescue all the unfortunate people, Jews as well, and give them equal rights...Socialism's victory would spell the only effective defeat of the forces of anti-Semitism".'' He further maintains that he met socialist [[Gentile]]s who ridded themselves of anti-Semitism upon discovering socialism. The enemy is the capitalist, whether Gentile or Jewish; and the Jewish poor are his friend.<ref name="Stern2018">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y5BNDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA24|title=Jewish Materialism: The Intellectual Revolution of the 1870s|author=Eliyahu Stern|date=20 March 2018|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0-300-22180-0|pages=24–}}</ref>
Feigenbaum rejected Zionism as utopian and urged Jews to reject notion of ''[[Jewish diaspora|Goles]]'' as exile from [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]], but rather state of persecution, from which socialism can redeem them.<ref name="Zimmerman2004" />
==Death== Feigenbaum died on the morning of November 10, 1932 in the [[St Barnabas Hospital (Bronx)|Home for Incurables]] in New York. He had been ill for the previous ten years, the last three of which he was paralyzed. Funeral services were held in Forward Hall, on November 13, 1932. Feigenbaum is currently buried in the [[Workmen's Circle|Workmen’s Circle]] section of [[Mount Carmel Cemetery (Queens, New York)|Mount Carmel Cemetery]], in [[Queens]], [[New York City|New York]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.jta.org/1932/11/11/archive/funeral-services-sunday-for-feigenbaum-socialist-leader|title=Funeral Services Sunday for Feigenbaum, Socialist Leader {{!}} Jewish Telegraphic Agency|website=www.jta.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-27}}</ref>
