{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}} {{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}} {{Infobox Christian leader | type = Bishop | name = Joseph Albert Rosario, M.S.F.S | title = [[Bishop]] of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Amravati|Diocese of Amravati]] (Emeritus) |image = Picture of Bishop Rosario.png | alt = | caption = | church = [[Roman Catholic Church]] | archdiocese = | diocese = | see = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Amravati|Diocese of Amravati]] | term = 1955–1995 | predecessor = '''None''' | successor = Edwin Colaço <!-- Orders --> | ordination = 29 September 1944 | ordinated_by = | consecration = | consecrated_by = | rank = <!-- Personal details --> | birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1915|5|30}} | birth_place = [[Nagpur]], [[India]] [[File:Flag of India.svg|25px]] | death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|2011|7|31|1915|5|30}} | death_place = | previous_post = Priest }}
'''Joseph Albert Rosario''', M.S.F.S (30 May 1915 – 31 July 2011) was an Indian [[prelate]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]]. He was one of oldest Roman Catholic Bishops and the oldest Bishop from India.
Rosario was born in [[Nagpur]], India on 30 May 1915. He was ordained priest on 29 September 1944 <ref>{{Catholic-hierarchy|bishop|brosar|Bishop Joseph Albert Rosario, M.S.F.S.|21 January 2015}}</ref> in the [[religious institute]] of the [[Missionaries of St. Francis de Sales]]. Appointed on 8 May 1955 to the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Amravati|Diocese of Amravati]], he was ordained bishop on 13 November 1955, retiring from governance of the see on 1 April 1995.
==Popularity== Bishop Rosario was very popular among the non-Catholic masses of [[Amravati]]. He was particularly known in the region for his tolerance for other religions
