[[File:Study of Charon 1 Félix Resurrección Hidalgo.jpg|thumb|A boatman of the netherworld drawn by [[Félix Resurrección Hidalgo]]]] '''Urshanabi''' was the ferryman of the [[Hubur]], river of the dead in [[Mesopotamian mythology]]. His equivalent in [[Greek Mythology]] was [[Charon (mythology)|Charon]].<ref name="George2003"/>
He is first mentioned in the myth of [[Enlil and Ninlil]], where he is called '''SI.LU.IGI''' and described as a man.<ref name="ETCSL">[http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/etcsl.cgi?text=t.1.2.1&charenc=j# Enlil and Ninlil., Black, J.A., Cunningham, G., Robson, E., and Zólyomi, G., The Electronic Text Corpus of Sumerian Literature, Oxford 1998-.]</ref> In the [[Epic of Gilgamesh]], Urshanabi is a companion of [[Gilgamesh]] after [[Enkidu]] dies. They meet when Urshanabi is involved in the [[curious]] occupation of collecting an unintelligible type of "''urnu''-[[snake]]s" in the forest. Urshanabi's ferry is at first powered by unintelligible "stone things", that are destroyed by Gilgamesh, who proceeds to power the boat with 120 stakes he has to make to replace the "stone-things". He is banished from [[Kur]] by the immortal survivor of the flood [[Utnapishtim]] for no discernible reason, possibly for conveying Gilgamesh across the Hubur. They both ferry back to [[Uruk]] where they behold its splendour. His later [[Assyria|Assyrian]] incarnation is called '''Hamar-tabal''', who is described as a horrible monster.<ref name="George2003">{{cite book|author=A. R. George|title=The Babylonian Gilgamesh epic: introduction, critical edition and cuneiform texts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=21xxZ_gUy_wC&pg=PA500|accessdate=7 June 2011|year=2003|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-927841-1|pages=500–}}</ref>
==See also== * [[Manunggul Jar]] - Early depiction similar figure on burial jar from [[Tabon Caves]] on [[Palawan]]
